SIMPLE: inheritance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inheritance
<hw>In*her"it*ance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF.
<ets>enheritance</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or state of inheriting; <as>as, the
<ex>inheritance</ex> of an estate; the <ex>inheritance</ex> of mental or
physical qualities.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is or may be inherited; that which is
derived by an heir from an ancestor or other person; a heritage; a
possession which passes by descent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When the man dies, let the <qex>inheritance</qex>⟦br⟧
Descend unto the daughter.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A permanent or valuable possession or blessing, esp.
one received by gift or without purchase; a benefaction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To an <qex>inheritance</qex> incorruptible, and undefiled, and
that fadeth not away.</q> <rj><qau>1 Pet. i. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Possession; ownership; acquisition.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>inheritance</xex> of their loves.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To you th' <qex>inheritance</qex> belongs by right⟦br⟧
Of brother's praise; to you eke 'longs his love.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>Transmission and reception by
animal or plant generation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>A perpetual or continuing right
which a man and his heirs have to an estate; an estate which a man has
by descent as heir to another, or which he may transmit to another as
his heir; an estate derived from an ancestor to an heir in course of
law.</def> <rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The word <xex>inheritance</xex> (used simply) is mostly
confined to the title to land and tenements by a descent.</note>
<rj><au>Mozley & W.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men are not proprietors of what they have, merely for themselves;
their children have a title to part of it which comes to be wholly
theirs when death has put an end to their parents' use of it; and this
we call <qex>inheritance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>inherited</ent>⟦br⟧
